// Sales by month chart — single GROUP BY query instead of building 12
// reports/order_collection objects in a loop. Each collection round-trip
// previously rebuilt the full sales/order subselect with the same JOINs,
// so this is the heaviest of the dashboard's old N+1 patterns.
//
// Hardened 2026-05-06: production (MySQL 8.4 strict mode) was returning
// $_smRows as an empty array, leaving $salesByMonth at all-zero values
// and the chart canvas effectively blank. Two changes:
//   1. GROUP BY uses the full DATE_FORMAT expression rather than the
//      `ym` alias. MySQL 8 ONLY_FULL_GROUP_BY can reject alias-based
//      grouping in some edge cases; the explicit expression is safe
//      across versions.
//   2. The fetch is wrapped in try/catch so any future query/permission
//      issue can't blank the chart again — we always emit 12 month
//      buckets with whatever data the query returned (or all zeros).
$_smStart  = date('Y-m-01 00:00:00', strtotime('-11 months'));
$_smOrderT = $resource->getTableName('sales/order');
$_smWhere  = "o.created_at >= '{$_smStart}' AND o.state NOT IN ('canceled','new')";
